### Consistency
A theory is considered consistent if it does not contain any contradictions. In other words, it is impossible to derive both a statement and its negation from the theory. If a theory proves itself, it does not necessarily mean it is inconsistent; it could still be consistent if it does not derive contradictions.

### Tautological
A tautology is a statement that is always true, regardless of the truth values of its components. In the context of a theory, a tautology would be a statement that is provable within the theory and is true by definition. For example, the statement "P or not P" (the law of excluded middle) is a tautology in classical logic.

